'''Freda Josephine Baker''' ({{née|'''McDonald'''}}; June 3, 1906 – April 12, 1975), naturalized as '''Joséphine Baker''', was an American-born French dancer, singer, and actress. Her career was centered primarily in Europe, mostly in France. She was the first black woman to star in a major motion picture, the 1927 French silent film ''[[Siren of the Tropics]]'', directed by {{lang|fr|Mario Nalpas|italic=no}} and {{lang|fr|[[Henri Étiévant]]|italic=no}}.<ref>{{cite book |last = Atwood |first = Kathryn |title = Women Heroes of World War II |publisher= Chicago Review Press |year = 2011 |isbn = 978-1-55652-961-0 |page = 77 }}</ref>

During her early career, Baker was among the most celebrated performers to headline the revues of the {{lang|fr|[[Folies Bergère]]|italic=no}} in [[Paris]]. Her performance in its 1927 revue {{lang|fr|Un vent de folie}} caused a sensation in the city. Her costume, consisting only of a short skirt of artificial bananas and a beaded necklace, became an iconic image and a symbol both of the [[Jazz Age]] and the [[Roaring Twenties]]. Baker was celebrated by artists and intellectuals of the era, who variously dubbed her the "Black Venus", the "Black Pearl", the "Bronze Venus", and the "Creole Goddess".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Anderson |first=Victoria Clarice |title=Highlighting Black + LGBT Pioneers: Josephine Baker |url=https://www.believeoutloud.com/voices/article/highlighting-black-lgbt-pioneers-josephine-baker/ |access-date=2023-02-11 |website=Believe Out Loud |archive-date=February 11, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230211205646/https://www.believeoutloud.com/voices/article/highlighting-black-lgbt-pioneers-josephine-baker/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Born in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], she renounced her U.S. citizenship and became a [[French nationality law#Dual citizenship|French national]] after her marriage to French industrialist Jean Lion in 1937.<ref name="Kelleher">{{cite web |last1 = Kelleher |first1 = Katy |title = She'll Always Have Paris |url = https://jezebel.com/5502673/shell-always-have-paris |website = Jezebel |access-date = 13 October 2016 |date = 26 March 2010 |archive-date = 18 October 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161018201017/http://jezebel.com/5502673/shell-always-have-paris |url-status = live }}</ref> She raised her children in France.

Baker aided the [[French Resistance]] during [[World War II]].<ref name="QR" /> After the war, she was awarded the [[Resistance Medal]] by the [[French Committee of National Liberation]], the {{lang|fr|[[Croix de guerre 1939–1945|Croix de Guerre]]|italic=no}} by the [[French military]], and was named a [[Chevalier of the Legion of Honour]] by General [[Charles de Gaulle]].<ref name="Remembering Josephine Baker">{{cite news |last = Roberts |first = Kimberly |title = Remembering Josephine Baker |newspaper = [[Philadelphia Tribune]] |date = April 8, 2011 }}</ref> Baker sang: "I have two loves: my country and Paris."<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/josephine-baker-life-artist-activist-170602194956917.html |title = Josephine Baker: The life of an artist and activist |publisher = [[Al Jazeera Arabic|Al Jazeera]] |access-date = 3 June 2017 |archive-date = 3 June 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170603013724/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/josephine-baker-life-artist-activist-170602194956917.html |url-status = live }}</ref> On November 30, 2021, Baker was inducted into the [[Panthéon]] in Paris, the first black woman to receive one of the highest honors in France.<ref name="Angelique Chrisafis">{{cite news |date = 30 November 2021 |title = Josephine Baker, music hall star and civil rights activist, enters Panthéon |url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/nov/30/black-french-american-rights-activist-josephine-baker-enters-pantheon |first=Angelique |last=Chrisafis|access-date = 30 November 2021 |newspaper = The Guardian |language = en |archive-date = 30 November 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211130171108/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/nov/30/black-french-american-rights-activist-josephine-baker-enters-pantheon |url-status = live }}</ref> As her resting place remains in [[Monaco Cemetery]], a [[cenotaph]] was installed in vault 13 of the crypt in the Panthéon.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.lemonde.fr/culture/live/2021/11/30/josephine-baker-au-pantheon-suivez-en-direct-la-ceremonie_6104186_3246.html |title = Joséphine Baker au Panthéon : retrouvez l'intégralité de la cérémonie |language = fr |trans-title = Joséphine Baker at the Pantheon: transcript of the entire ceremony |date = 30 November 2021 |website = [[Le Monde]] |access-date = 30 November 2021 |archive-date = 30 November 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211130184724/https://www.lemonde.fr/culture/live/2021/11/30/josephine-baker-au-pantheon-suivez-en-direct-la-ceremonie_6104186_3246.html |url-status = live }}</ref>

Baker, who refused to perform for [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregated]] audiences in the United States, is also noted for her contributions to the [[civil rights movement]]. In 1968, she was offered unofficial leadership in the movement in the United States by [[Coretta Scott King]], following [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]'s [[Assassination of Martin Luther King Jr.|assassination]]. After thinking it over, Baker declined the offer out of concern for the welfare of her children.<ref name="jeanclaude2a">{{cite book |last = Baker |first = Jean-Claude |title = Josephine: The Hungry Heart |edition = 1st |publisher = Random House |year = 1993 |isbn = 978-0-679-40915-1 |url = https://archive.org/details/josephinehungryh00bake }}</ref><ref name="Bouillon">{{cite book |last = Bouillon |first = Joe |title = Josephine |edition = 1st |publisher = Harper & Row |year = 1977 |isbn = 978-0-06-010212-8 |url = https://archive.org/details/josephine00bake }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.radiofrance.fr/franceculture/podcasts/grandes-traversees-josephine-baker/5-la-mort-en-scene-3588148 |title=sur France Culture, radio), in french |access-date=August 12, 2022 |archive-date=December 7, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221207132150/https://www.radiofrance.fr/franceculture/podcasts/grandes-traversees-josephine-baker/5-la-mort-en-scene-3588148 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Early life==
[[File:Joséphine Baker enfant - médaillon.jpg|thumb|Baker, {{circa}} 1908]]

Josephine Baker was born Freda Josephine McDonald in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref name="jeanclaude2a"/><ref name="bm">{{cite web|title=Josephine Baker (Freda McDonald) Native of St. Louis, Missouri|url=http://blackmissouri.com/digest/josephine-baker-freda-mcdonald-native-of-st-louis-missouri.html|work=Black Missouri|date=10 February 2008|access-date=6 March 2009}}</ref><ref name="va">{{cite web|title=About Art Deco – Josephine Baker|url=http://www.vam.ac.uk/vastatic/microsites/1157_art_deco/about|publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]]|access-date=6 March 2009|date=2015-07-29}}</ref> Baker's ancestry is unknown&mdash;her mother, Carrie, was adopted in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], in 1886 by Richard and Elvira McDonald, both of whom were former [[slavery|slaves]] of African and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] descent.<ref name="jeanclaude2a"/> Baker's estate identifies vaudeville drummer Eddie Carson as her natural father despite evidence to the contrary.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Josephine Baker: Biography |work=Official site of Josephine Baker |url=http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |year=2008 |access-date=2009-01-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109063301/http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |archive-date=9 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1993, Josephine Baker's foster son [[Jean-Claude Baker]] published a biography titled ''Josephine: The hungry Heart'', which was the culmination of decades of exhaustive research into Baker's life and career. In the book, he discusses at length the circumstances surrounding Baker's birth:

{{blockquote|The records of the city of St. Louis tell an almost unbelievable story. They show that (Baker's mother) Carrie McDonald ... was admitted to the (exclusively white) Female Hospital on May 3, 1906, diagnosed as pregnant. She was discharged on June 17, her baby, Freda J. McDonald having been born two weeks earlier. Why six weeks in the hospital? Especially for a black woman (of that time) who would customarily have had her baby at home with the help of a midwife? ... The father was identified (on the birth certificate) simply as "Edw"... I think Josephine's father was white—so did Josephine, so did her family...people in St. Louis say that (Baker's mother) had worked for a German family (around the time she became pregnant)... I have unraveled many mysteries associated with Josephine Baker, but the most painful mystery of her life, the mystery of her father's identity, I could not solve. The secret died with Carrie, who refused to the end to talk about it. She let people think Eddie Carson was the father, and Carson played along, (but) Josephine knew better.<ref name="jeanclaude2a"/>}}

Josephine McDonald spent her early life on 212 Targee Street (known by some St. Louis residents as Johnson Street) in the [[Chestnut Valley]] neighborhood of St. Louis, a racially mixed low-income area near Union Station, consisting mainly of rooming houses, brothels, and apartments without indoor plumbing.<ref name="jeanclaude2a" /> She was poorly dressed, hungry as a child, and developed [[street smarts]] playing in the railroad yards of [[St. Louis Union Station|Union Station]].<ref>{{cite book |last = Wood |first = Ian |title = The Josephine Baker Story |year = 2000 |publisher = MPG Books |location = United Kingdom |isbn = 978-1-86074-286-6 |pages = [https://archive.org/details/josephinebakerst0000wood/page/241 241–318] |url = https://archive.org/details/josephinebakerst0000wood/page/241 }}</ref>

Her mother married Arthur Martin, "a kind but perpetually unemployed man", with whom she had a son and two more daughters.<ref>1920 United States Federal Census</ref> She took in laundry; her mother placed her there due to her family being impoverished;<ref>{{Cite web |title=Josephine Baker |url=https://www.milandes.com/en/josephine-baker/ |access-date=2024-12-18 |website=Le Château et jardins des Milandes |language=en-US}}</ref> she worked there in order to increase the income of her family and, at eight years old, Josephine began working as a live-in domestic for white families in St. Louis.<ref>{{cite book |last = Whitaker |first = Matthew C. |title = Icons of Black America: Breaking Barriers and Crossing Boundaries |year = 2011 |page = 64 }}</ref> One woman [[child abuse|abused]] her, burning Josephine's hands when the young girl put too much soap in the laundry.<ref>{{cite journal |title = The Rise and Fall of Josephine Baker |journal = [[Dollars & Sense]] |year = 1987 |volume = 13 }}</ref>

In 1917, when she was 11, a terrified Josephine McDonald witnessed [[East St. Louis riots|racial violence in East St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite web |last = Keyes |first = Allison |title = The East St. Louis Race Riot Left Dozens Dead, Devastating a Community on the Rise |url = https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smithsonian-institution/east-st-louis-race-riot-left-dozens-dead-devastating-community-on-the-rise-180963885/ |access-date = 29 August 2021 |website = Smithsonian Magazine |language = en |archive-date = 29 August 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210829235411/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smithsonian-institution/east-st-louis-race-riot-left-dozens-dead-devastating-community-on-the-rise-180963885/ |url-status = live }}</ref> In a speech years later, she recalled what she had seen:<blockquote>I can still see myself standing on the west bank of the Mississippi looking over into East St. Louis and watching the glow of the burning of Negro homes lighting the sky. We children stood huddled together in bewilderment ... frightened to death with the screams of the Negro families running across this bridge with nothing but what they had on their backs as their worldly belongings... So with this vision I ran and ran and ran...<ref name=":4">{{cite web |date = 2008-06-27 |title = Racial memory: Clear as black and white |url = https://news.stlpublicradio.org/government-politics-issues/2008-06-27/racial-memory-clear-as-black-and-white |access-date = 2021-08-29 |website = St. Louis Public Radio |language = en |archive-date = 29 August 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210829235413/https://news.stlpublicradio.org/government-politics-issues/2008-06-27/racial-memory-clear-as-black-and-white |url-status = live }}</ref></blockquote>

By age 12, she had dropped out of school.<ref>{{cite web |last = Matthews |first = Dasha |date = 26 February 2018 |title = The Activism of Josephine Baker |url = https://info.umkc.edu/womenc/2018/02/26/the-activism-of-josephine-baker/ |access-date = 6 September 2020 |website = UMKC Women's Center |archive-date = 3 October 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20201003065920/https://info.umkc.edu/womenc/2018/02/26/the-activism-of-josephine-baker/ |url-status = live }}</ref> At 13, she worked as a waitress at the Old Chauffeur's Club at 3133 Pine Street. She also lived as a [[street child]] in the slums of St. Louis, sleeping in cardboard shelters, scavenging for food in garbage cans,<ref name="Appel">{{cite book |last1 = Appel |first1 = Jacob M. |title = St. James Encyclopedia of Popular Culture |date = 2 May 2009 }}</ref> making a living with [[Street performance|street-corner dancing]]. It was at the Old Chauffeur's Club that Josephine met Willie Wells, whom she married at age 13, but the marriage lasted less than a year. Following her divorce from Wells, she found work with a street performance group called the Jones Family Band.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url = http://access-proxy.sno-isle.org/login?url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=ers&AN=88828615&site=eds-live&scope=site |title = Josephine Baker |last = Webb |first = Shawncey |encyclopedia = Salem Press Biographical Encyclopedia |year = 2016 |via = Research Starters, EBSCOhost }}</ref>

In her teens, she struggled to have a healthy relationship with her mother, who opposed her becoming an entertainer and scolded her for not tending to her second husband, William Howard Baker, whom she had married in 1921, at age 15.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baker, Josephine (1906–1975) |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/baker-josephine-1906-1975#:~:text=Uncertainty%20about%20her%20career%20and,had%20wed%20in%20June%201927|access-date=1 February 2022|website=www.encyclopedia.com|archive-date=1 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220201152115/https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/baker-josephine-1906-1975#:~:text=Uncertainty%20about%20her%20career%20and,had%20wed%20in%20June%201927|url-status=live}}</ref><!--<ref name="note" group=lower-alpha>Uncertainty about her career and her need for love and respectability made her consider marrying Pepito on whom she could depend, and who loved her. However, she was still married to Willie Baker, which didn't prevent the "couple" from announcing to the press that they had wed in June 1927.</ref>--> She soon left him when her vaudeville troupe was booked into a New York City venue. They divorced in 1925, during a period when her career success was beginning. Still, she continued to use his last name professionally for the rest of her life.<ref name="jeanclaude2a" /> Though Baker was often on the road, returning with gifts and money for her mother and younger half-sister, larger career opportunities drew her farther afield, to France.<ref>{{cite web |date = 29 November 2021 |title = Josephine Baker makes history as first Black woman honored in France's Pantheon |url = https://www.pbs.org/newshour/arts/josephine-baker-makes-history-as-first-black-woman-honored-in-frances-pantheon |access-date = 1 February 2022 |website = PBS NewsHour |language = en-us |archive-date = 1 February 2022 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20220201152116/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/arts/josephine-baker-makes-history-as-first-black-woman-honored-in-frances-pantheon |url-status = live }}</ref>

== Career ==
=== Early career ===
Baker's unrelenting badgering of a local show manager led to her recruitment for the St. Louis Chorus [[vaudeville]] act. At the age of 13, she headed to New York City<ref name=":4" /> during the [[Harlem Renaissance]] and performed at the Plantation Club, [[Florence Mills]]'s old stomping ground. After several auditions, she secured a role in the [[chorus line]] of a touring production of the groundbreaking and hugely successful [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] revue "[[Shuffle Along]]" (1921)<ref>{{cite book |title = The Oxford Companion to Jazz |editor = Kirchner, Bill |publisher = Oxford University Press |year = 2000 |page = [https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00kirc/page/700 700] |isbn = 978-0-19-512510-8 |url = https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00kirc/page/700 }}</ref> that helped bring public attention to Florence Mills, [[Paul Robeson]], and [[Adelaide Hall]].<ref>{{cite book |last = Williams |first = Iain Cameron |title = Underneath a Harlem Moon&nbsp;... The Harlem to Paris Years of Adelaide Hall |publisher = Continuum Int. Publishing |year = 2003 |isbn = 978-0-8264-5893-3 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = The real first lady of jazz |url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/biography.music |work = The Guardian |first = Stephen |last = Bourne |date = 24 January 2003 |access-date = 29 April 2013 |author-link = Stephen Bourne (writer) |archive-date = 17 October 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017180302/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/biography.music |url-status = live }}</ref>

In "Shuffle Along", Baker was a dancer at the end of a chorus line. Fearing she might be overshadowed by the others, she used her position to introduce a hint of comedy into her routine, making her stand out from her fellow dancers. She began in "Shuffle Along" with one of the U.S. touring companies, but, once she came of age, she was transferred to the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production, where she remained for several months, until the show closed, in 1923. Next, Baker was cast in "[[The Chocolate Dandies]]", a revue that opened on September 1, 1924. Again, she was relegated to the chorus line. The show ran for 96 performances, finally closing in November 1925.

=== Pre War Paris and rise to fame ===
[[File:Baker Banana.jpg|thumb|Baker in her banana costume, 1927]]
Baker sailed to Paris in 1925 and opened on October 2 in "{{ill|Revue nègre|fr|lt=la Revue nègre}}" at [[Théâtre des Champs-Élysées]].<ref name=JBwebsite>{{cite web |title = About Josephine Baker: Biography |work = Official Josephine Baker website |publisher = The Josephine Baker Estate |url = http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |year = 2008 |access-date = 12 January 2009 |archive-date = 9 November 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071109063301/http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Shack |first=W. A. |title=Harlem in Montmartre: A Paris Jazz Story Between the Great Wars |publisher=University of California Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-520-92569-4 |page=35}}</ref> She was 19 at the time. In a 1974 interview with ''[[The Guardian]]'', she explained that her first [[breakthrough role|big break]] came in this bustling European city:

{{blockquote|"No, I didn't get my first break on Broadway. I was only in the chorus in 'Shuffle Along' and 'Chocolate Dandies.' I became famous first in France in the twenties. I just couldn't stand America and I was one of the first [[colored|coloured]] Americans to move to Paris. Oh yes, [[Bricktop]] was there as well. Me and her were the only two, and we had a marvellous time. Of course, everyone who was anyone knew Bricky. And they got to know Miss Baker as well."<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |url = https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/aug/26/josephine-baker-interview-1974 |last = Murari |first = Tim |title = From the archive, 26 August 1974: An interview with Josephine Baker |journal = The Guardian |date = 26 August 2015 |access-date = 3 August 2018 |archive-date = 3 August 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180803074145/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/aug/26/josephine-baker-interview-1974 |url-status = live }}</ref>}}

In Paris, she became an instant success for her [[burlesque|erotic dancing]] and for appearing practically nude onstage. After a successful tour of Europe, she broke her contract and returned to France in 1926 to star at the [[Folies Bergère]], setting the standard for her future acts.<ref name="jeanclaude2a" />

[[File:Aankomst Josephine Baker-524881.ogv|thumb|Arrival of Baker in [[The Hague]], 1928]]
Baker performed the {{lang|fr|Danse Sauvage}}, wearing little more than a skirt of strung-together artificial bananas. Her success coincided with the 1925 {{lang|fr|[[Exposition des Arts Décoratifs]]}}, which gave birth to the term "[[Art Deco]]", as well as a renewed interest in non-Western art forms, including those of [[African art|African]] origin, which Baker would represent. In later shows in Paris, she was often accompanied on stage by her pet [[cheetah]], "Chiquita", donning a [[diamond]] collar. Chiquita frequently escaped into the [[orchestra pit]], terrorizing the musicians and adding another element of excitement to the show.<ref name="jeanclaude2a" />

After a while, Baker became the most successful American entertainer in France. [[Ernest Hemingway]] called her "the most sensational woman anyone ever saw."<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/quotes2.html |title='Quotes': the official Josephine Baker website |publisher = Cmgww.com |access-date = 5 December 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017051325/http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/quotes2.html |archive-date = October 17, 2013 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last = Lahs-Gonzales |first = Olivia |url = http://www.jazzreview.com/book/review-380.html |title = Josephine Baker: Image & Icon |work = Jazz Book Review |year = 2006 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091025094658/http://www.jazzreview.com/book/review-380.html |archive-date = 25 October 2009 }}</ref> The author spent hours talking with her in Parisian bars. [[Picasso]] depicted her alluring beauty. [[Jean Cocteau]] became friendly with her and helped vault her to international stardom.<ref name="Guardian"/> Baker endorsed a "Bakerfix" hair gel, as well as bananas, shoes, and cosmetics, among other products.{{sfnp|Bergfelder|Harris|Street|2007|pp=191–198}}

In 1929, Baker became the first African-American star to visit [[Yugoslavia]], which she included on a tour through [[Central Europe]] via the [[Orient Express]]. In [[Belgrade]], she performed at Luxor Balkanska, then the city's most luxurious venue. In a nod to local culture, she included a [[Pirot carpet|Pirot kilim]] in her routine, and donated some of the show's proceeds to poor children of [[Serbia]]. In [[Zagreb]], adoring crowds greeted her at the train station, but opposition from local [[clergy]] and morality police led to the cancellation of some of her shows.<ref name=":3">{{cite web |last = Esha |title = Josephine Baker in Yugoslavia |url = https://historicly.substack.com/p/josephine-baker-in-yugoslavia |access-date = July 5, 2020 |website = historicly.substack.com |date = July 4, 2020 |archive-date = July 5, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200705215344/https://historicly.substack.com/p/josephine-baker-in-yugoslavia |url-status = live }}</ref>

During her travels in Yugoslavia, Baker was accompanied by "Count" Giuseppe Pepito Abatino.<ref name=":3" /> At the start of her career in France, Abatino, a [[Sicily#Demographics|Sicilian]] former [[stonemason]] who passed himself off as a [[count]], persuaded her to let him manage her.<ref name=":1">{{cite AV media|title=Chasing a Rainbow: The Life of Josephine Baker|last=Ralling|first=Christopher|year=1987}}</ref> He became not only Baker's manager, but her lover as well. The two could not marry because she was not yet divorced from her second husband, Willie Baker.{{sfnp|Jules-Rosette|2007|p={{page needed|date=September 2021}}}}

During this period, she released her most successful song, "J'ai deux amours" (1931).<ref>{{cite book |last = Asante |first = Molefi Kete |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=RLY6-CsAE68C&pg=PA277 |title = The African American People: A Global History |year = 2013 |publisher = Routledge |isbn = 978-1-136-50677-2 |page = 277 |access-date = July 5, 2020 |archive-date = August 4, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200804004348/https://books.google.com/books?id=RLY6-CsAE68C&pg=PA277 |url-status = live }}</ref> The song expresses the sentiment that "I have two loves, my country and Paris." In a 2007 book, Tim Bergfelder, Sue Harris, and Sarah Street claimed that "by the 1930's, Baker's assimilation into French popular culture had been completed by her association with the song."{{sfnp|Bergfelder|Harris|Street|2007|p=193}} She starred in four films, which found success only in Europe: the [[silent film]] ''[[Siren of the Tropics]]'' (1927), ''[[Zouzou (film)|Zouzou]]'' (1934) and ''[[Princesse Tam Tam]]'' (1935). She starred in ''Fausse Alerte'' in 1940.<ref name="Encyclopedia" /> Bergfelder, Harris, and Street wrote that the silent film ''Siren of the Tropics'' "rehearses the 'primitive-to-Parisienne' narrative that would become the staple of Baker's cinema career, and exploited in particular her comic stage persona based on loose-limbed athleticism and artful clumsiness."{{sfnp|Bergfelder|Harris|Street|2007|p=193}} The [[sound film]]s "Zouzou" (1934) and "Princesse Tam Tam" were both [[star vehicle]]s for Baker.{{sfnp|Bergfelder|Harris|Street|2007|pp=193–197}}

[[File:Louis Gaudin - Casino de Paris - Josephine Baker 1930.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Drawing by Louis Gaudin, depicting Baker being presented a [[flower bouquet]] by a cheetah]]
[[File:Joséphine Baker par Jean Chassaing.jpg|thumb|A stylized depiction of Baker in a poster by Jean Chassaing, from 1931.]]

Under the management of Abatino, Baker's stage and public persona, as well as her singing voice, were transformed. In 1934, she took the lead in a revival of [[Jacques Offenbach]]'s opera ''[[La créole]]'', which premiered in December of that year for a six-month run at the [[Théâtre Marigny]] on the [[Champs-Élysées]] of Paris. In preparation for her performances, she went through months of training with a vocal coach. In the words of [[Shirley Bassey]], who has cited Baker as her primary influence, "...&nbsp;she went from a {{lang|fr|petite danseuse sauvage}} with a decent voice to {{lang|fr|la grande diva magnifique}}...&nbsp;I swear in all my life I have never seen, and probably never shall see again, such a spectacular singer and performer."<ref name=":2">{{cite web |title = Josephine Baker: The First Black Super Star |url = http://www.allblackwoman.com/josephine-baker-the-first-black-super-star |work = Allblackwoman.com |date = June 4, 2012 |access-date = 18 June 2012 |archive-date = 8 June 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120608210433/http://www.allblackwoman.com/josephine-baker-the-first-black-super-star/ |url-status = live }}</ref>

Despite her popularity in [[France]], Baker never attained the equivalent reputation in [[America]]. Her star turn in a 1936 revival of "[[Ziegfeld Follies of 1936|Ziegfeld Follies]]" on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] was not commercially successful, and later in the run she was replaced by [[Gypsy Rose Lee]].<ref name="Schroeder">{{cite book |last1 = Schroeder |first1 = Alan |first2=Heather Lehr |last2=Wagner |title = Josephine Baker: Entertainer |year = 2006 |publisher = Chelsea House Publications |isbn = 978-0-7910-9212-5 |pages = 51–52 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pelF1O7b2xwC&pg=PA51 |access-date = January 27, 2016 |archive-date = August 24, 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210824025531/https://books.google.com/books?id=pelF1O7b2xwC&pg=PA51 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Cullen |first = Frank |title = Vaudeville, Old and New: An Encyclopedia of Variety Performers in America, 2 volumes |year = 2006 |publisher = Routledge |isbn = 978-0-415-93853-2 |page = 235 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XFnfnKg6BcAC&pg=PA235 |access-date = February 20, 2016 |archive-date = August 24, 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210824025552/https://books.google.com/books?id=XFnfnKg6BcAC&pg=PA235 |url-status = live }}</ref>''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine referred to her as a "Negro wench ... whose dancing and singing might be topped anywhere outside of Paris", while other critics said her voice was "too thin" and "dwarf-like" to fill the [[Winter Garden Theatre]].<ref name="Schroeder" /> She returned to Europe heartbroken.<ref name="JBwebsite" /> This contributed to Baker's becoming a legal citizen of France and giving up her American citizenship.<ref name="jeanclaude2a" />

Baker returned to Paris in 1937, married the French industrialist Jean Lion, and became a French citizen.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.gibbsmagazine.com/Josephine%20Baker.htm |title = Josephine Baker |first = Susan |last = Robinson |work = Gibbs Magazine |date = June 3, 1906 |access-date = December 5, 2013 |archive-date = 28 May 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130528130056/http://www.gibbsmagazine.com/Josephine%20Baker.htm |url-status = live }}</ref> They were married in the French town of [[Crèvecœur-le-Grand]], in a wedding presided over by the mayor, Jammy Schmidt.

Between 1933 and 1937, Baker was a guest at the start of the [[Tour de France]] on four occasions.<ref>{{cite web |last = McKay |first = Feargal |title = When Josephine Baker Sprinkled Her Stardust on the Tour de France |url = https://www.podiumcafe.com/book-corner/2021/10/14/22643648/josephine-baker-tour-de-france |url-status = live |access-date = October 17, 2021 |website = Podium Café |date = October 14, 2021 |archive-date = October 17, 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211017180833/https://www.podiumcafe.com/book-corner/2021/10/14/22643648/josephine-baker-tour-de-france }}</ref>

In 1938, after enduring severe hostility in Germany and Eastern Europe during the late 1920s—where she was targeted by storm troopers with ammonia bombs and told to "Go back to Africa"—Josephine Baker became a French citizen by marrying Jean Lion in 1937. This significant event in her life spurred her to actively participate in the French Resistance against the Nazis.<ref name="Liverpool University Press">{{Cite book |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctt1ps31v4 |title=Deferred Dreams, Defiant Struggles: Critical Perspectives on Blackness, Belonging, and Civil Rights |date=2018-07-04 |publisher=Liverpool University Press |isbn=978-1-78694-820-5 |editor-last=Johnson |editor-first=Violet Showers |doi=10.2307/j.ctt1ps31v4.7 |jstor=j.ctt1ps31v4 |editor-last2=Graml |editor-first2=Gundolf |editor-last3=Lessane |editor-first3=Patricia Williams}}</ref>

=== World War II ===
[[File:Baker Harcourt 1948.jpg|thumb|Baker in uniform, 1948]]
In September 1939, when France declared war on Germany in response to the invasion of Poland, Baker was recruited by the [[Deuxième Bureau]], the French military intelligence agency, as an "honorable correspondent".  Baker worked with Jacques Abtey, the head of French [[counterintelligence]] in Paris.
She socialized with the Germans at embassies, ministries, night clubs, charming them while secretly gathering information. Her café-society fame enabled her to rub shoulders with those in the know, from high-ranking Japanese officials to Italian and [[Vichy]] bureaucrats, reporting to Abtey what she heard. She attended parties and gathered information at the Italian embassy without raising suspicion.{{sfnp|Rose|1989|pp=182–269}} Baker's espionage work went beyond merely gathering information at social events. She collected detailed intelligence on German troop movements, as well as the locations and activities of airfields and harbors. Confident in her celebrity status and the protections it afforded, Baker believed she could operate without raising suspicion. To covertly transport sensitive information, she used ingenious methods, such as writing notes on her hands and arms, pinning them inside her clothing, and using invisible ink. Her boldness paid off, allowing her to smuggle intelligence across borders and deliver critical reports to the French Resistance.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-02-01 |title=Siren of the Resistance: The Artistry and Espionage of Josephine Baker |url=https://www.nationalww2museum.org/war/articles/siren-resistance-artistry-and-espionage-josephine-baker |access-date=2024-12-18 |website=The National WWII Museum {{!}} New Orleans |language=en}}</ref>

When the Germans invaded France, Baker left Paris and went to the [[Château des Milandes]], her home in the [[Dordogne]] {{lang|fr|[[département]]}} in the south of France. The Château des Milandes became, especially in World War II, one of the most important hideaways; She would shelter resistance fighters and Jewish refugees, providing them with documents and even money for food, cloth, and forged documents she usually financed herself. Her estate also provided the center of resistance activities, including the installation of a radio transmitter in order to be in touch with the Allied forces and storing weapons in its cellar.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wright |first=Jennifer |date=2022-07-16 |title=Josephine Baker was a badass resistance spy |url=https://nypost.com/2022/07/16/josephine-baker-was-a-badass-resistance-spy/ |access-date=2024-12-18 |language=en-US}}</ref>  As an entertainer, Baker had an excuse for moving around Europe, visiting neutral nations such as Portugal, as well as some in South America. She carried information for transmission to England, about airfields, harbors, and German troop concentrations in the West of France. Notes were written in invisible ink on Baker's sheet music.{{sfnp|Rose|1989|pp=232–269}}<ref>{{Cite web |title=Josephine Baker's Sheet Music |url=https://www.spymuseum.org/exhibition-experiences/about-the-collection/collection-highlights/josephine-baker-s-sheet-music/ |access-date=2023-03-24 |website=International Spy Museum |language=en |archive-date=March 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230324195030/https://www.spymuseum.org/exhibition-experiences/about-the-collection/collection-highlights/josephine-baker-s-sheet-music/ |url-status=live }}</ref> As described in ''Jazz Cleopatra'', "She specialized in gatherings at [[embassies]] and ministries, charming people as she had always done, but at the same time trying to remember interesting items to transmit".<ref name=":3" />

Later in 1941, she and her entourage went to the [[French colonies]] in North Africa. The stated reason was Baker's health (since she was recovering from another case of pneumonia), but the real reason was to continue helping the Resistance. From a base in Morocco, she made tours of Spain. She pinned notes with the information she gathered inside her underwear. She met the [[Thami El Glaoui|Pasha of Marrakech]], whose support helped her through a miscarriage (the last of several). After the miscarriage, she developed an infection so severe it required a [[hysterectomy]]. The infection spread and she developed [[peritonitis]] and then [[sepsis]]. After her recovery (which she continued to fall in and out of), she started touring to entertain British, French, and American soldiers in North Africa. The Free French had no organized entertainment network for their troops, so Baker and her entourage managed for the most part on their own. They allowed no civilians and charged no admission.{{sfn|Rose|1989|p=200}}

After the war, Baker was awarded the [[Resistance Medal]] by the [[French Committee of National Liberation]], the {{lang|fr|[[Croix de guerre 1939–1945|Croix de Guerre]]|italic=no}} by the [[French military]], and was named a [[Légion d'honneur|Chevalier of the {{lang|fr|Légion d'honneur|nocat=y}}]] by General [[Charles de Gaulle]].<ref name="Remembering Josephine Baker"/>

Baker's last marriage, to French composer and conductor [[Jo Bouillon]], ended around the time she adopted her 11th child.{{sfnp|Jules-Rosette|2007|p={{page needed|date=September 2021}}}}

=== Post War ===
[[File:Josephine Baker 1950.jpg|thumb|Baker in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], in 1950]]
[[File:Josephine Baker in Amsterdam, Bestanddeelnr 906-3468.jpg|thumb|210px|Baker in [[Amsterdam]], 1954]]
In 1949, a reinvented Baker returned in triumph to the Folies Bergère. Bolstered by recognition of her wartime heroism, Baker the performer assumed a new gravitas, unafraid to take on serious music or subject matter. The engagement was a rousing success and reestablished Baker as one of Paris' pre-eminent entertainers. In 1951, Baker was invited back to the United States for a nightclub engagement in Miami. After winning a public battle over desegregating the club's audience, Baker followed up her sold-out run at the club with a national tour. Rave reviews and enthusiastic audiences accompanied her everywhere, climaxed by a parade in Harlem in honor of her new title: [[NAACP]]'s "Woman of the Year".<ref>{{cite web |last = Joyce |first = Dr Robin |date = March 5, 2017 |title = Josephine Baker, 1906–1975 |url = https://womenshistorynetwork.org/josephine-baker-1906-1975/ |access-date = September 6, 2020 |website = Women's History Network |language = en-GB |archive-date = September 26, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200926075054/https://womenshistorynetwork.org/josephine-baker-1906-1975/ |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date = May 25, 2014 |title = Josephine Baker hero |work = Heroes: What They Do & Why We Need Them |url = https://blog.richmond.edu/heroes/tag/josephine-baker-hero/ |access-date = 6 September 2020 |publisher = [[University of Richmond]] |archive-date = 8 February 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180208214355/http://blog.richmond.edu/heroes/tag/josephine-baker-hero/ |url-status = live }}</ref>

In 1952, Baker was hired to crown the Queen of the Cavalcade of Jazz for the famed eighth [[Cavalcade of Jazz]] concert held at [[Wrigley Field (Los Angeles)|Wrigley Field]] in Los Angeles, which was produced by [[Leon Hefflin, Sr.]] on June 1. Also featured to perform that day were [[Roy Brown (blues musician)|Roy Brown]] and His Mighty Men, [[Anna Mae Winburn]] and Her Sweethearts, [[Toni Harper]], [[Louis Jordan]], [[Jimmy Witherspoon]] and [[Jerry Wallace]].<ref>{{cite book |title = The Black music history of Los Angeles, its roots: 50 years in Black music: a classical pictorial history of Los Angeles Black music of the 20s, 30s, 40s, 50s and 60s: photographic essays that define the people, the artistry and their contributions to the wonderful world of entertainment |last = Reed |first = Tom |date = 1992 |publisher = Black Accent on L.A. Press |isbn = 978-0-9632908-6-1 |edition = 1st, limited |location = Los Angeles |oclc = 28801394 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Josephine Baker to Crown Queen |department = Headliner |work = Los Angeles Sentinel |date = May 22, 1952 }}{{page needed|date=April 2022}}</ref>

An incident at the [[Stork Club]] in October 1951 interrupted and overturned her plans. Baker criticized the club's unwritten policy of discouraging Black patrons, then scolded columnist [[Walter Winchell]], an old ally, for not rising to her defense. Winchell responded swiftly with a series of harsh public rebukes, including accusations of [[Communist]] sympathies (a serious charge at the time). The ensuing publicity resulted in the termination of Baker's work visa, forcing her to cancel all her engagements and return to France. It was almost a decade before U.S. officials allowed her back into the country.<ref name="firestorm" />

In January 1966, [[Fidel Castro]] invited Baker to perform at the "Teatro Musical de La Habana" in [[Havana]], Cuba, at the seventh-anniversary celebrations of his revolution. Her spectacular show in April broke attendance records. In 1968, Baker visited Yugoslavia and made appearances in Belgrade and in [[Skopje]]. In her later career, Baker faced financial troubles. She commented, "Nobody wants me, they've forgotten me"; but family members encouraged her to continue performing. In 1973 she performed at [[Carnegie Hall]] to a standing ovation.{{sfn|Rose|1989|p=251}}

The following year, she appeared in a [[Royal Variety Performance]] at the [[London Palladium]], and then at the [[Red Cross of Monaco|Monegasque Red Cross Gala]], celebrating her 50 years in French show business. Advancing years and exhaustion began to take their toll; she sometimes had trouble remembering lyrics, and her speeches between songs tended to ramble. She still continued to captivate audiences of all ages.{{sfn|Rose|1989|p=257}}

== Civil rights activism ==
Although based in France, Baker supported the [[American Civil Rights Movement]] during the 1950s. When she arrived in New York with her husband Jo, they were refused reservations at 36 hotels because of racial discrimination. This led her to write several articles about segregation in the United States. She also traveled in the South, giving a talk at [[Fisk University]], a [[historically black college]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], on "France, North Africa and the Equality of the Races in France".{{sfn|Rose|1989|p=209}} In the 1950s the FBI tracked everything she did; opening a file on her. The intent of doing so was to deter other countries from allowing her to take the stage. During her travels to foreign countries, she would leverage her influence to bring light to the racial discrimination in the United States which created a rift between her and her homeland.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dudziak |first=Mary L. |date=September 1994 |title=Josephine Baker, Racial Protest, and the Cold War |url=https://academic.oup.com/jah/article-lookup/doi/10.2307/2081171 |journal=The Journal of American History |volume=81 |issue=2 |pages=543–570 |doi=10.2307/2081171|jstor=2081171 }}</ref>

On October 16, 1951, Josephine Baker experienced a public incident where she was said to have been refused service at the upscale Stork Club in New York City. Determined to expose this injustice, Baker set out to publicize her story, expecting support from one of America's most powerful conservative journalists and one of the regulars at the club: Walter Winchell. Instead of solidarizing with Baker, Winchell launched a media attack on her. He labeled her as an anti-American communist sympathizer, which turned the public attention away from the discrimination she had to face. This was an incident that proved that, on one hand, Baker faced racism, while on the other, influential people were also up against her efforts to fight against the same. Undaunted by such opposition, she continued to use her platform to advocate for civil rights and challenge systemic injustice.<ref name="Liverpool University Press"/>

She refused to perform for segregated audiences in the United States, although she was offered $10,000 by a Miami club;<ref name="QR">{{cite journal |last = Bostock |first = William W. |title = Collective Mental State and Individual Agency: Qualitative Factors in Social Science Explanation |journal = Forum Qualitative Sozialforschung |volume = 3 |issue = 3 |year = 2002 |issn = 1438-5627 |url = http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0114-fqs020317 |access-date = 20 September 2009 |archive-date = 24 August 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210824025540/https://www.qualitative-research.net/index.php/fqs/article/view/835 |url-status = live }}</ref> the club eventually met her demands. Her insistence on mixed audiences helped to integrate live entertainment shows in the [[Las Vegas Valley]].<ref name="Bouillon" /> After this incident, she began receiving threatening phone calls from people claiming to be from the [[Ku Klux Klan]] but said publicly that she was not afraid of them.{{sfn|Rose|1989|p=212}}

In 1951, Baker made charges of racism against [[Sherman Billingsley]]'s [[Stork Club]] in Manhattan, where she had been refused service.<ref name=firestorm>{{cite news |url = http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/firestorm-incident-stork-club-1951-article-1.571278 |title = Firestorm Incident at the Stork Club, 1951 |author = Hinckley, David |date = 9 November 2004 |newspaper = Daily News |location = New York |access-date = February 29, 2016 |archive-date = March 5, 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305074546/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/firestorm-incident-stork-club-1951-article-1.571278 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4TgoAAAAIBAJ&pg=6956,1502149&dq=stork+club+baker&hl=en |title = Stork Club Refused to Serve Her, Josephine Baker Claims |date = 19 October 1951 |newspaper = [[Milwaukee Journal]] |access-date = 29 August 2010 }}{{dead link|date=October 2021 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Actress [[Grace Kelly]], who was at the club at the time, rushed over to Baker, took her by the arm and stormed out with her entire party, vowing never to return (although she returned on 3 January 1956 with [[Prince Rainier of Monaco]]). The two women became close friends after the incident.<ref>{{cite book |last = Spoto |first = Donal |title = High Society: The Life of Grace Kelly |date = 2009 |publisher = Harmony Books |isbn = 978-0-307-46251-0 |location = New York |page = 63 |oclc = 496121174 }}</ref>

When Baker was near bankruptcy, Kelly—by then the [[princess consort]]—offered her a villa and financial assistance. (During his work on the "Stork Club" book, author and "[[New York Times]]" reporter Ralph Blumenthal was contacted by [[Jean-Claude Baker]], one of Baker's sons. He indicated that he had read his mother's [[FBI]] file and, using comparison of the file to the tapes, said he thought the Stork Club incident was overblown.<ref name="Society">{{cite news |url = http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/stork-club-special-delivery-exhibit-new-york-historical-society-recalls-glamour-wind-article-1.873537 |title = Stork Club Special Delivery Exhibit at the New York Historical Society recalls a glamour gone with the wind |author = Kissel, Howard |date = 3 May 2000 |access-date = April 23, 2018 |work = Daily News |archive-date = October 11, 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161011060954/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/stork-club-special-delivery-exhibit-new-york-historical-society-recalls-glamour-wind-article-1.873537 |url-status = live }}</ref>)

Baker also worked with the [[NAACP]].<ref name="QR" /> Her reputation as a crusader grew to such an extent that the NAACP had Sunday, May 20, 1951, declared "Josephine Baker Day". She was presented with life membership with the NAACP by [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winner [[Ralph Bunche]]. The honor she was paid spurred her to further her crusading efforts with the "[[Willie McGee (convict)|Save Willie McGee]]" rally. McGee was a black man in Mississippi convicted of raping a white woman in 1945 on the basis of dubious evidence, and sentenced to death.{{sfnp|Dittmer|1994|p=21}} Baker attended rallies for McGee and wrote letters to [[Fielding Wright]], the governor of Mississippi, asking him to spare McGee's life.{{sfnp|Dittmer|1994|p=21}} Despite her efforts, McGee was executed in 1951.{{sfnp|Dittmer|1994|p=21}} As the decorated war hero who was bolstered by the racial equality she experienced in Europe, Baker became increasingly regarded as controversial; some black people even began to shun her, fearing that her outspokenness and racy reputation from her earlier years would hurt the cause.{{sfn|Rose|1989|p=205}}

In 1963, she spoke at the [[March on Washington]] at the side of Rev. [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web |last = Rustin |first = Bayard |title = Profiles in Courage for Black History Month |url = http://nbjc.org/news/black-history-profile-5.html |publisher = [[National Black Justice Coalition]] |date = February 28, 2006 |access-date = January 8, 2009 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110720135849/http://nbjc.org/news/black-history-profile-5.html |archive-date = July 20, 2011 }}</ref> Baker was the only official female speaker. While wearing her [[Free French]] uniform emblazoned with her medal of the Légion d'honneur, she introduced the "Negro Women for Civil Rights".<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.infoplease.com/spot/marchonwashington.html |title = Civil Rights March on Washington |publisher = Infoplease.com |date = 28 August 1963 |access-date = 5 December 2013 |archive-date = 4 December 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131204144003/http://www.infoplease.com/spot/marchonwashington.html |url-status = live }}</ref> [[Rosa Parks]] and [[Daisy Bates (civil rights activist)|Daisy Bates]] were among those she acknowledged, and both gave brief speeches.<ref name="Baker" /> Not everyone involved wanted Baker present at the March; some thought her time overseas had made her a woman of France, one who was disconnected from the Civil Rights issues going on in America. In her speech, one of the things Baker said:

<blockquote>I have walked into the palaces of kings and queens, and into the houses of presidents and much more. But I could not walk into a hotel in America and get a cup of coffee, and that made me mad. And when I get mad, you know that I open my big mouth. And then look out, 'cause when Josephine opens her mouth, they hear it all over the world ...<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/march-on-washington-had-one-female-speaker-josephine-baker/2011/08/08/gIQAHqhBaJ_story.html |title = March on Washington had one female speaker: Josephine Baker |newspaper = The Washington Post |language = en |access-date = 2018-09-19 |archive-date = September 19, 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180919211453/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/march-on-washington-had-one-female-speaker-josephine-baker/2011/08/08/gIQAHqhBaJ_story.html |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.blackpast.org/1963-josephine-baker-speech-march-washington |title = (1963) Josephine Baker, 'Speech at the March on Washington' |work = The Black Past: Remembered and Reclaimed |date = 3 November 2011 |language = en |access-date = 2018-09-19 |archive-date = 20 September 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180920010915/http://www.blackpast.org/1963-josephine-baker-speech-march-washington |url-status = live }}</ref></blockquote>

After King's assassination, his widow [[Coretta Scott King]] approached Baker in the Netherlands to ask if she would take her husband's place as leader of the Civil Rights Movement. After many days of thinking it over, Baker declined, saying her children were "too young to lose their mother."<ref name="Baker">{{cite book |last = Baker |first = Josephine |author2 = Bouillon, Joe |title = Josephine |edition = 1st |location = New York |publisher = Harper & Row |year = 1977 |isbn = 978-0-06-010212-8 |url = https://archive.org/details/josephine00bake }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Parker |first=Najja |title=Josephine Baker: France could claim her, America couldn't tame her |url=https://www.ajc.com/entertainment/josephine-baker-france-could-claim-her-and-america-couldn-tame-her/R95DUfFOXflmIAEwIsA70K/ |access-date=2024-01-31 |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |language=English |issn=1539-7459}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
=== Relationships ===
[[File:JosephineBaker1964NL.jpg|thumb|Baker with ten of her adopted children, 1964]]
Baker's first marriage was to American [[Pullman porter]] Willie Wells when she was only 13 years old. The union was reportedly very unhappy, and the couple divorced soon after marrying. Another short-lived marriage followed in 1921, to William Howard Baker. Since her career was already taking off under that last name, she retained it after the divorce. Jean-Claude Baker wrote that Josephine was [[Bisexual community|bisexual]] and had several relationships with women.<ref name=Garber>{{cite book |last = Garber |first = Marjorie |title = Bisexuality and the Eroticism of Everyday Life |publisher = Routledge |year = 2013 |page = 122 |isbn = 978-0-415-92661-4 }}</ref>

In 1925, she began an extramarital relationship with the [[Belgians|Belgian]] novelist [[Georges Simenon]].<ref>{{cite book |last = Assouline |first = P. |title = Simenon, A Biography |publisher = Knopf |year = 1997 |pages = 74–75 |isbn = 978-0-679-40285-5 }}</ref>  On an ocean liner, in 1929,  en route from South America to France, Baker had an affair with the Swiss-French architect [[Le Corbusier]] (Charles-Édouard Jeanneret).<ref>{{cite book | url=https://academic.oup.com/book/9306/chapter-abstract/156047661?redirectedFrom=fulltext | doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199354016.003.0005 | chapter=4: Jazz in Stone and Steel: Josephine Baker and Modern Architecture | title=Some of These Days: Black Stars, Jazz Aesthetics, and Modernist Culture | date=2015 | last1=Donald | first1=James | pages=107–130 | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19-935401-6 | access-date=September 7, 2022 | archive-date=September 7, 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220907205148/https://academic.oup.com/book/9306/chapter-abstract/156047661?redirectedFrom=fulltext | url-status=live }}</ref> In 1937, Baker married Frenchman Jean Lion, but they separated in 1940. She married French composer and conductor Jo Bouillon in 1947, and their union lasted 14 years before also ending in [[divorce]]. Later, she was involved with the artist Robert Brady for a time, but they never married.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |title = Josephine Baker |work = cmgww.com |access-date = 23 August 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071109063301/http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |archive-date = 9 November 2007 |url-status = dead }}</ref> Speculation exists that Baker was also involved in sexual liaisons, if not relationships, with blues singer [[Clara Smith]], [[Ada "Bricktop" Smith]], French novelist [[Colette]], and [[Frida Kahlo]].<ref name="Garber" /><ref>{{cite web |last = Strong |first = Lester Q. |year = 2006 |title = Baker, Josephine (1906–1975) |url = http://www.glbtqarchive.com/arts/baker_josephine_A.pdf |url-status = live |archive-date = 2 August 2020 |access-date = 3 June 2020 |website = GLBTQ Archive |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200802180100/http://www.glbtqarchive.com/arts/baker_josephine_A.pdf }}</ref>

=== Children ===
[[File:Afhalen van Josephine Baker in Frankrijk Josephine in haar tuin Les Milandes, Bestanddeelnr 912-6479.jpg|thumb|Baker at the [[Château des Milandes]], 1961]]

During her participation in the [[civil rights movement]], Baker began to adopt children, forming a family which she often referred to as "The Rainbow Tribe". Baker wanted to prove that "children of different [[ethnicities]] and [[religions]] could still be brothers." She often took the children with her cross-country, and when they were at [[Château des Milandes]], she arranged tours so visitors could walk the grounds and see how natural and happy the children were in "The Rainbow Tribe".<ref>{{cite web |title = Biography |url = http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |publisher = Josephine Baker Estate |access-date = 16 October 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071109063301/http://www.cmgww.com/stars/baker/about/biography.html |archive-date = 9 November 2007 |url-status = dead }}</ref> Her estate featured hotels, a farm, rides, and the children singing and dancing for the audience. She charged an admission fee to visitors who entered and partook in the activities, which included watching the children play.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/history/2014/04/josephine_baker_s_rainbow_tribe_before_madonna_and_angelina_jolie_the_expat.html |title = Josephine Baker's Rainbow Tribe |last = Onion |first = Rebecca |date = 18 April 2014 |work = Slate |access-date = 19 September 2018 |language = en-US |issn = 1091-2339 |archive-date = 19 September 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180919212742/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/history/2014/04/josephine_baker_s_rainbow_tribe_before_madonna_and_angelina_jolie_the_expat.html |url-status = live }}</ref>

She created dramatic backstories for them, picking them with clear intent in mind: at one point, she wanted and planned to adopt a [[Jewish]] baby, but she settled for a French one. She also raised them in different religions in order to further her model for the world, taking two children from [[Algeria]] and raising one child as a [[Muslim]] and raising the other child as a [[Catholic]]. One member of the Tribe, Jean-Claude Baker, said: "She wanted a doll".<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/10765330/Would-the-perfect-family-contain-a-child-from-every-race.html |title = Would the perfect family contain a child from every race? |last = Guterl |first = Matthew Pratt |journal = The Daily Telegraph |date = 19 April 2014 |access-date = 19 September 2018 |language = en-GB |issn = 0307-1235 |archive-date = 19 September 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180919211605/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/10765330/Would-the-perfect-family-contain-a-child-from-every-race.html |url-status = live }}</ref>

Baker raised two daughters, French-born Marianne and [[Morocco|Moroccan]]-born Stellina, and 10 sons, [[Japan]]ese-born Janot (born Teruya) and Akio,<ref>{{cite web |last=Denéchère |first=Yves |title=Josephine Baker's 'Rainbow Tribe' and the pursuit of universal brotherhood |url=https://theconversation.com/josephine-bakers-rainbow-tribe-and-the-pursuit-of-universal-brotherhood-172714 |website=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |date=November 30, 2021 |access-date=December 25, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=December 25, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221225202205/https://theconversation.com/josephine-bakers-rainbow-tribe-and-the-pursuit-of-universal-brotherhood-172714 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Fornés |first1=Nora G. |title=Joséphine Baker's son: 'For us, her most obvious legacy is tolerance' |url=https://english.elpais.com/culture/2022-11-17/josephine-bakers-son-for-us-her-most-obvious-legacy-is-tolerance.html |website=[[EL PAÍS]] |access-date=25 December 2022 |language=en-us |date=17 November 2022 |archive-date=December 25, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221225202205/https://english.elpais.com/culture/2022-11-17/josephine-bakers-son-for-us-her-most-obvious-legacy-is-tolerance.html |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Colombia]]n-born Luis, [[Finland|Finnish]]-born Jari (now Jarry), French-born Jean-Claude, Noël, and Moïse, [[Algeria]]n-born Brahim (later Brian), [[Ivory Coast|Ivorian]]-born Koffi, and [[Venezuela]]n-born Mara.<ref>{{cite book |first = Stephen |last = Papich |title = Remembering Josephine |year = 1976 |url = https://archive.org/details/rememberingjosep0000papi |page = 149 |publisher = Bobbs-Merrill |isbn = 978-0-672-52257-4 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Josephine Baker Biography |url = http://www.lkwdpl.org/wihohio/bake-jos.htm |work = Women in History |year = 2008 |access-date = 12 January 2009 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090118134952/http://lkwdpl.org/wihohio/bake-jos.htm |archive-date = 18 January 2009 }}</ref> Later on, Josephine Baker would become the legal guardian of another boy, also named [[Jean-Claude Baker|Jean-Claude]], and considered him an unofficial addition to the Rainbow Tribe. For some time, Baker lived with her children and an enormous staff in the château in [[Dordogne]], France, with her fourth husband, Jo Bouillon. Bouillon claimed that Baker bore one child, though it was stillborn in 1941, an incident that precipitated an emergency hysterectomy.{{sfnp|Jules-Rosette|2007|page=190}}

Baker forced Jarry to leave the château and live with his adoptive father, Jo Bouillon, in [[Argentina]], at the age of 15, after discovering that he was [[gay]] (though it appears that the two were able to reconcile in later years.)<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC World Service - The Outlook Podcast Archive, Josephine Baker: My mother, the superstar singer and spy - Part 2 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p09sc506 |website=BBC |date=17 August 2021}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |last1=Von Merlind |first1=Theile |title=Josephine Baker's Rainbow Tribe |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/adopting-the-world-josephine-baker-s-rainbow-tribe-a-652613.html |newspaper=Der Spiegel |date=October 2, 2009 |access-date=October 9, 2021 |archive-date=October 9, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211009184714/https://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/adopting-the-world-josephine-baker-s-rainbow-tribe-a-652613.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.artfixdaily.com/artwire/release/5212-josephine-baker-exhibit-jarry-baker-attending-on-behalf-of-jean-c |title = Josephine Baker Exhibit: Jarry Baker Attending on Behalf of Jean-Claude Baker |website = Artifax Daily |date = 21 July 2019 |access-date = 30 November 2021 |language = en-US |url-status = live |archive-date = 29 November 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211129165111/http://www.artfixdaily.com/artwire/release/5212-josephine-baker-exhibit-jarry-baker-attending-on-behalf-of-jean-c }}</ref> Moïse died of cancer in 1999, and Noël was diagnosed with schizophrenia and is in a psychiatric hospital as of 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last = Theile |first = Merlind |title = Josephine Baker's Rainbow Tribe |url = https://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/adopting-the-world-josephine-baker-s-rainbow-tribe-a-652613.html |website = Der Spiegel |date = 2 October 2009 |access-date = 9 October 2021 |archive-date = 9 October 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211009184714/https://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/adopting-the-world-josephine-baker-s-rainbow-tribe-a-652613.html |url-status = live }}</ref> [[Jean-Claude Baker]], the unofficial addition to the Rainbow Tribe, committed [[suicide]] in 2015, aged 71.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/16/nyregion/jean-claude-baker-a-restaurateur-dies-at-71.html?partner=rssnyt&emc=rss&_r=0 |title = Jean-Claude Baker Dies at 71; Restaurateur Honored a Chanteuse |last = Weber |first = Bruce |work = [[The New York Times]] |date = 15 January 2021 |access-date = 29 November 2021 |archive-date = 2 October 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181002230639/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/16/nyregion/jean-claude-baker-a-restaurateur-dies-at-71.html?partner=rssnyt&emc=rss&_r=0 |url-status = live }}</ref>

== Later years and death ==
In her later years Baker converted to [[Catholicism]].<ref name=Gale>{{cite web |title = Josephine Baker |work = Notable Black American Women |year = 1992 |url = https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/K1623000015/BIC |url-access = subscription |via = Gale in Context: Biography |access-date = 9 September 2021 |archive-date = 9 September 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210909141514/https://galeapps.gale.com/apps/auth?userGroupName=&origURL=https%3A%2F%2Fgo.gale.com%2Fps%2Fi.do%3Fp%3DBIC%26u%3D%26id%3DGALE%7CK1623000015%26v%3D2.1%26it%3Dr&prodId=BIC |url-status = live }}</ref> In 1968, Baker lost her château owing to unpaid debts; afterwards [[Princess Grace]] offered her an apartment in [[Roquebrune-Cap-Martin|Roquebrune]], near [[Monaco]].<ref>{{cite book |title = Josephine Baker and the Rainbow Tribe |author = Guterl, Matthew |publisher = Belknap Press |year = 2014 |page = 154 |isbn = 978-0-674-04755-6 }}</ref>

Baker was back on stage at the [[Olympia (Paris)|Olympia]] in [[Paris]] in 1968, in [[Belgrade]] and at [[Carnegie Hall]] in 1973 and at the Royal Variety Performance at the [[London Palladium]] and at the "Gala du Cirque" in Paris in 1974. On April 8, 1975, Baker starred in a retrospective revue at the [[Bobino]] in Paris, "Joséphine à Bobino 1975" celebrating her 50 years in show business. The revue, financed by [[Prince Rainier]], Princess Grace, and [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]], opened to rave reviews. Demand for seating was such that fold-out chairs had to be added to accommodate spectators. The opening-night audience included [[Sophia Loren]], [[Mick Jagger]], [[Shirley Bassey]], [[Diana Ross]] and [[Liza Minnelli]].<ref name="AABaker">{{cite web |title = African American Celebrity Josephine Baker, Dancer and Singer |url = http://www.africanamericans.com/JosephineBaker.htm |work = AfricanAmericans.com |year = 2008 |access-date = 12 January 2009 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090102041450/http://www.africanamericans.com/JosephineBaker.htm |archive-date = 2 January 2009 }}</ref>

Four days later, Baker was found lying peacefully in her bed surrounded by newspapers with glowing reviews of her performance. She was in a coma after suffering a [[cerebral hemorrhage]]. She was taken to [[Pitié-Salpêtrière Hospital]], where she died, aged 68, on April 12, 1975.<ref name="AABaker" /><ref name=obit>{{cite news |title = Josephine Baker Is Dead in Paris at 68 |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1975/04/13/archives/josephine-baker-is-dead-in-paris-at-68.html |page = 60 |work = The New York Times |date = 13 April 1975 |access-date = 12 January 2009 |archive-date = 23 February 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170223200529/http://www.nytimes.com/1975/04/13/archives/josephine-baker-is-dead-in-paris-at-68.html |url-status = live }}</ref>

Baker received a full [[Catholic funeral]] at [[L'Église de la Madeleine]], attracting more than 20,000 mourners.<ref name="Gale" /><ref>{{cite journal |url = http://escholarship.org/uc/item/4jq1f16w#page-16 |title = Josephine Baker: A Chanteuse and a Fighter |journal = Journal of Transnational American Studies |volume = 2 |issue = 1 |access-date = 27 June 2014 |date = 30 March 2010 |last1 = Ara |first1 = Konomi |doi = 10.5070/T821006983 |doi-access = free |archive-date = 14 July 2014 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140714205500/http://escholarship.org/uc/item/4jq1f16w#page-16 |url-status = live }}</ref> The only American-born woman to receive full French military honors at her funeral, Baker's funeral was the occasion of a huge procession. After a family service at [[Saint-Charles Church, Monaco|Saint-Charles Church]] in [[Monte Carlo]],<ref name="Company1975">{{cite magazine |first = Charles L. |last = Sanders |title = Josephine Baker's Estate May Exceed $3 Million |magazine = Jet4 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HVsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28 |date = 15 May 1975 |pages = 26–29 |issn = 0021-5996 |access-date = 20 February 2016 |archive-date = 10 January 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170110071828/https://books.google.com/books?id=HVsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28 |url-status = live }}</ref> Baker was interred at the {{lang|fr|[[Monaco Cemetery|Cimetière de Monaco]]}}.<ref name="AABaker" /><ref name=desbornesmonacocimetiere>{{cite news |last1 = Verany |first1 = Cedric |title = Monaco Cimetière: des bornes interactives pour retrouver les tombes |url = http://archives.monacomatin.mc/article/societe/monaco-cimetiere-des-bornes-interactives-pour-retrouver-les-tombes.41578.html |access-date = 26 December 2015 |work = [[Monaco Matin]] |date = 1 November 2008 |archive-date = 27 December 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151227064339/http://archives.monacomatin.mc/article/societe/monaco-cimetiere-des-bornes-interactives-pour-retrouver-les-tombes.41578.html |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=amisperemonaco>{{cite web |title = Visite funéraire de Monaco |url = http://www.appl-lachaise.net/appl/article.php3?id_article=59 |website = Amis et Passionés du Père-Lachaise |date = 30 August 2005 |access-date = 26 December 2015 |archive-date = 26 December 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151226234058/http://www.appl-lachaise.net/appl/article.php3?id_article=59 |url-status = dead }}</ref>

Baker was a [[Freemason]].<ref>{{Cite web |author=Masonic Order of Universal Co-Freemasonry |title=Masonic Biographies {{!}} Josephine Baker |url=https://www.universalfreemasonry.org/en/famous-freemasons/josephine-baker |access-date=2023-06-15 |website=Universal Co-Masonry |language=en |archive-date=April 2, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230402014415/https://www.universalfreemasonry.org/en/famous-freemasons/josephine-baker |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Legacy ==
[[File:Place Joséphine Baker (Paris) - panneau.JPG|thumb|Place Joséphine Baker in [[Paris]]]]
"Place Joséphine Baker" ({{coord|48.84135|2.32375|region:FR_dim:50|format=dms|name=place Joséphine Baker}}) in the [[Montparnasse Quarter]] of Paris was named in her honor. She has also been inducted into the [[St. Louis Walk of Fame]],<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.stlouiswalkoffame.org/inductees/?view=achievement |title = St. Louis Walk of Fame Inductees |last =  |publisher = stlouiswalkoffame.org |access-date = April 25, 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121031162946/http://www.stlouiswalkoffame.org/inductees/?view=achievement |archive-date = 31 October 2012 |url-status = dead }}</ref> and on March 29, 1995, into the [[Hall of Famous Missourians]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.house.mo.gov/famous.aspx?fm=4 |title = Hall of Famous Missourians |publisher = Missouri House of Representatives |date = 29 March 1995 |access-date = 5 December 2013 |archive-date = October 23, 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131023190213/http://www.house.mo.gov/famous.aspx?fm=4 |url-status = live }}</ref> St. Louis's Channing Avenue was renamed Josephine Baker Boulevard,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mohistory.org/collections/item/resource:145007|title=Junction of Channing Avenue (Josephine Baker Boulevard) with Lindell Boulevard and Olive Street.|author=Missouri Historical Society Lab |website=The Missouri Historical Society is ... Missouri Historical Society and was founded in 1866.|language=en|access-date=29 July 2019|archive-date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729195329/https://mohistory.org/collections/item/resource:145007|url-status=live}}</ref> and a wax sculpture of Baker is on permanent display at [[The Griot Museum of Black History]].

In 2015, she was inducted into the [[Legacy Walk]] in [[Chicago, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wasserman |first=Melissa |url = http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/m/APPredirect.php?AID=53131 |title = Legacy Walk unveils five new bronze memorial plaques |newspaper = Windy City Times |access-date = 3 June 2017 |archive-date = 21 April 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200421031425/http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/m/APPredirect.php?AID=53131 |url-status = live }}</ref> The Piscine Joséphine Baker is a swimming pool along the banks of the Seine in Paris named after her.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.paris.fr/pratique/piscines/piscine-josephine-baker/p6085 |title = Piscine Joséphine Baker |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140220030557/http://www.paris.fr/pratique/piscines/piscine-josephine-baker/p6085 |archive-date = 20 February 2014 |website = paris.fr |access-date = 3 June 2017 |language = fr }}</ref>

Writing in the online ''BBC Magazine'' in late 2014, Darren Royston, historical dance teacher at [[RADA]], credited Baker with being the [[Beyoncé]] of her day, and bringing the Charleston to Britain.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-30051234 |title = What do twerking and the Charleston have in common? |work = BBC Magazine Monitor |date = 17 November 2014 |access-date = 18 November 2014 |archive-date = 18 November 2014 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141118011835/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-30051234 |url-status = live }}</ref> Two of Baker's sons, Jean-Claude and Jarry (Jari), grew up to go into business together, running the restaurant Chez Josephine on Theatre Row, [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]], New York City. It celebrates Baker's life and works.<ref>{{cite web |title = Chez Josephine |url = http://www.chezjosephine.com/jean-claude.html |publisher = Jean-Claude Baker |year = 2009 |access-date = 13 January 2009 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090401205934/http://www.chezjosephine.com/jean-claude.html |archive-date = 1 April 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:Château des Millandes.jpg|thumb|[[Château des Milandes]], which Baker rented from 1940, before purchasing in 1947.]]
[[Château des Milandes]], a castle near Sarlat in the [[Dordogne]], was Baker's home where she raised her twelve children. It is open to the public and displays her stage outfits including her banana skirt (of which there are apparently several). It also displays many family photographs and documents as well as her [[Legion of Honour]] medal. Most rooms are open for the public to walk through including bedrooms with the cots where her children slept, a huge kitchen, and a dining room where she often entertained large groups. The bathrooms were designed in art deco style but most rooms retained the French chateau style.<ref>{{cite news |last = Crosley |first = Sloane |date = 12 July 2016 |title = Exploring the France That Josephine Baker Loved |language = en-US |work = [[The New York Times]] |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/17/travel/josephine-baker-paris-france.html |access-date = 6 September 2020 |issn = 0362-4331 |archive-date = 3 October 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20201003222049/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/17/travel/josephine-baker-paris-france.html |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last = Milne |first = Andrew |date = 29 October 2019 |title = Spend a day with Josephine Baker in her beloved château |url = https://us.france.fr/en/dordogne-valley/article/josephine-baker-chateau-des-milandes |access-date = 6 September 2020 |website = Explore France |language = en |archive-date = 23 October 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20201023220130/https://us.france.fr/en/dordogne-valley/article/josephine-baker-chateau-des-milandes |url-status = live }}</ref>

Baker continued to influence celebrities more than a century after her birth. In a 2003 interview with ''USA Today'', [[Angelina Jolie]] cited Baker as "a model for the multiracial, multinational family she was beginning to create through adoption."<ref name="Kraut" /> Beyoncé performed Baker's banana dance at the [[Fashion Rocks]] concert at [[Radio City Music Hall]] in September 2006.<ref name=Kraut>{{cite journal |last = Kraut |first = Anthea |date = Summer 2008 |title = Review: 'Josephine Baker in Art and Life: The Icon and the Image' by Bennetta Jules-Rosette |journal = [[Dance Research Journal]] |volume = 40 |issue = 1 |pages = 83–86 |jstor = 20527595 |doi = 10.1017/S014976770000139X |s2cid = 191289759 }}</ref>

As a commemoration of Baker's one hundredth birthday, a multi-media performance was written and shown in 2006. The following year, Josephine Baker: A Life of Le Jazz Hot! was recorded from the Baker inspired production by Imani Winds.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Josephine Baker |url=https://imaniwinds.com/josephine-baker |access-date=2024-03-10 |website=Imani Winds |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Blair |first=Elizabeth |date=June 11, 2007 |title=Imani Winds Hits Its Mark on 'Josephine Baker' |url=https://www.npr.org/2007/06/11/10947999/imani-winds-hits-its-mark-on-josephine-baker |website=NPR}}</ref>

Writing on the 110th anniversary of her birth, ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' described how her 1926 "danse sauvage" in her famous banana skirt "brilliantly manipulated the white male imagination" and "radically redefined notions of race and gender through style and performance in a way that continues to echo throughout fashion and music today, from [[Prada]] to Beyoncé."<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.vogue.com/13442586/josephine-baker-90th-anniversary-banana-skirt/ |title = 90 Years Later, the Radical Power of Josephine Baker's Banana Skirt |work = Vogue |first = Morgan |last = Jerkins |date = 3 June 2016 |access-date = 30 January 2017 |archive-date = 26 January 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170126090910/http://www.vogue.com/13442586/josephine-baker-90th-anniversary-banana-skirt |url-status = live }}</ref>

On June 3, 2017, the 111th anniversary of her birth, [[Google]] released an animated [[Google Doodle]], which consists of a slideshow chronicling her life and achievements.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.refinery29.com/2017/06/157349/google-doodle-josephine-baker-entertainer-activist/ |title = Google Doodle Honors Jazz Age Icon & Civil Rights Activist Josephine Baker |work = Refinery 29 |first = Madeleine |last = Buxton |date = 3 June 2017 |access-date = 3 June 2017 |archive-date = 4 June 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170604185547/http://www.refinery29.com/2017/06/157349/google-doodle-josephine-baker-entertainer-activist |url-status = live }}</ref>

On Thursday, November 22, 2018, a documentary entitled ''Josephine Baker: The Story of an Awakening'', directed by Ilana Navaro, premiered at the Beirut Art Film Festival. It contains rarely seen archival footage, including some never before discovered, with music and narration.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.terranoa.com/product/product.php?code=2314 |title = Josephine Baker: The Story of an Awakening |access-date = 15 October 2019 |archive-date = 15 October 2019 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191015035209/http://www.terranoa.com/product/product.php%3Fcode%3D2314 |url-status = live}}</ref>

In August 2019, Baker was one of those inducted in the [[Rainbow Honor Walk]], a [[walk of fame]] in San Francisco's [[Castro District]] noting [[LGBTQ]] people who have "made significant contributions in their fields".<ref>{{cite web |url = https://sfist.com/2014/09/02/castros_rainbow_honor_walk_dedicate/ |title = Castro's Rainbow Honor Walk Dedicated Today |last = Barmann |first = Jay |date = 2 September 2014 |website = SFist |access-date = 15 August 2019 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190810075052/https://sfist.com/2014/09/02/castros_rainbow_honor_walk_dedicate/ |archive-date = 10 August 2019 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name="autogenerated7">{{cite web |url = https://www.ebar.com/news/news//277209 |title = Castro to see more LGBT honor plaques |last = Bajko |first = Matthew S. |date = 5 June 2019 |website = The [[Bay Area Reporter]] |language = en |access-date = 16 August 2019 |archive-date = 14 August 2019 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190814193946/https://www.ebar.com/news/news//277209 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web |url = https://www.kqed.org/news/11765805/tributes-in-bronze-8-more-lgbt-heroes-join-s-f-s-rainbow-honor-walk |title = Tributes in Bronze: 8 More LGBT Heroes Join S.F.'s Rainbow Honor Walk |last = Yollin |first = Patricia |date = 6 August 2019 |website = KQED: The California Report |language = en |access-date = 16 August 2019 |archive-date = 14 August 2019 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190814132643/https://www.kqed.org/news/11765805/tributes-in-bronze-8-more-lgbt-heroes-join-s-f-s-rainbow-honor-walk |url-status = live }}</ref>

The [[Staatliche Museen zu Berlin]] (Berlin State Museums) hosted an exhibition "Josephine Baker: Icon in Motion" from January 26 through April 28, 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Berlin |first=Staatliche Museen zu |title=Josephine Baker |url=https://www.smb.museum/en/exhibitions/detail/josephine-baker/ |access-date=2024-01-31 |website=www.smb.museum |language=en}}</ref> The show displays photographs, film, and drawings covering her entertainment career through her involvement in civil rights. The exhibit includes Baker inspired works by her contemporaries.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2024-01-30 |title=Josephine Baker, Still Moving |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/01/30/arts/design/josephine-baker-exhibition-berlin.html |access-date=2024-01-31 |language=en |last1=Labarge |first1=Emily }}</ref>

Josephine Baker appears on the French 20-cent euro coins released in March 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-10 |title=Veil, Baker and Curie: acclaimed women to appear on new French coins |url=https://www.rfi.fr/en/france/20240310-veil-baker-and-curie-acclaimed-women-to-appear-on-new-french-coins |access-date=2024-03-15 |website=RFI |language=en}}</ref>

=== Panthéon in Paris ===
[[File:Joséphine Baker au Panthéon - illustration de JipéDan.jpg|thumb|Baker in the [[Panthéon]]]]
In May 2021, an online petition was set up by writer Laurent Kupferman asking that Joséphine Baker be honoured by being reburied at the [[Panthéon]] in Paris or being granted Panthéon honours, which would make her only the sixth woman at the mausoleum alongside [[Simone Veil]], [[Geneviève de Gaulle-Anthonioz]], [[Marie Curie]], [[Germaine Tillion]], and [[Sophie Berthelot]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Aude |last=Mazoue |date = 30 May 2021 |title = Petition seeks to honour French Resistance hero Joséphine Baker at the Panthéon |url = https://www.france24.com/en/france/20210530-france-petitions-to-have-josephine-baker-honoured-with-voltaire-rousseau-at-the-panth%C3%A9on |access-date = 31 May 2021 |publisher = France 24 |language = en |archive-date = 1 June 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210601004415/https://www.france24.com/en/france/20210530-france-petitions-to-have-josephine-baker-honoured-with-voltaire-rousseau-at-the-panth%C3%A9on |url-status = live }}</ref> In August 2021 the French President, [[Emmanuel Macron]], announced that Baker's remains would be reburied at the Panthéon in November 2021, following the petition and continued requests from Baker's family since 2013.<ref>{{cite web |date = 22 August 2021 |title = Musical legend Josephine Baker to enter France's Pantheon |url = https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20210822-musical-legend-josephine-baker-to-enter-france-s-pantheon |access-date = 22 August 2021 |publisher = [[France 24]] |language = en |archive-date = 22 August 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210822110553/https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20210822-musical-legend-josephine-baker-to-enter-france-s-pantheon |url-status = live }}</ref> Her son Claude Bouillon-Baker, however, told [[Agence France-Presse]] that her body would remain in Monaco and only a plaque would be installed at the Panthéon.<ref>{{cite web |date = 23 August 2021 |title = First black woman to enter French Panthéon of heroes |url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-58303919 |access-date = 24 August 2021 |website = BBC News |language = en-GB |archive-date = 24 August 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210824092049/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-58303919 |url-status = live }}</ref> It was later announced that a symbolic casket containing soil from various locations where Baker had lived, including St. Louis, Paris, the South of France and Monaco, would be carried by the [[French Air and Space Force]] in a parade in Paris before a ceremony at the Panthéon where the casket was interred.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.today.com/news/josephine-baker-becomes-first-black-woman-honored-frances-panthe-rcna7050 |title = Josephine Baker becomes first Black woman honored at France's Panthéon |first = Drew |last = Weisholtz |website = Today |date = 30 November 2021 |access-date = 30 November 2021 |language = en-US |url-status = live |archive-date = 30 November 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211130155718/https://www.today.com/news/josephine-baker-becomes-first-black-woman-honored-frances-panthe-rcna7050 }}</ref> The ceremony took place on Tuesday, November 30, 2021, and Baker thus became the first black woman to be honored in the secular temple to the "great men" of the French Republic.<ref>{{cite news |first=Claire |last=Gatinois |date = 30 November 2021 |title = La force symbolique de l'entrée au Panthéon de Joséphine Baker, "combattante de la liberté" |language = fr |work = Le Monde.fr |url = https://www.lemonde.fr/culture/article/2021/11/30/la-force-symbolique-de-l-entree-au-pantheon-de-josephine-baker-combattante-de-la-liberte_6104109_3246.html |access-date = 30 November 2021 |archive-date = 30 November 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211130171108/https://www.lemonde.fr/culture/article/2021/11/30/la-force-symbolique-de-l-entree-au-pantheon-de-josephine-baker-combattante-de-la-liberte_6104109_3246.html |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name="Angelique Chrisafis" />

== Works portraying or inspired by Baker ==

=== Film and television ===
[[Diana Ross]] portrayed Baker in her [[Tony Award]]-winning Broadway and television show "[[An Evening with Diana Ross]]". When the show was made into an NBC television special entitled ''The Big Event: An Evening with Diana Ross'', Ross again portrayed Baker.<ref>{{cite web |title = An Evening With Diana Ross (1977) |url = http://dianarossproject.wordpress.com/tag/an-evening-with-diana-ross-1977 |work = dianarossproject |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-date = 24 October 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131024103732/http://dianarossproject.wordpress.com/tag/an-evening-with-diana-ross-1977/ |url-status = live }}</ref> In the 1981 film ''[[Das Boot]], a'' German submariner mimics Baker's {{lang|fr|Danse banane}}.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Baer |first=Hester |date=Winter 2012 |title='Das Boot' and the German Cinema of Neoliberalism |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/41494715 |url-status=live |journal=The German Quarterly |publisher=Wiley on behalf of the American Association of Teachers of German |volume=85 |page=34 |doi=10.1111/j.1756-1183.2012.00135.x |jstor=41494715 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210916095835/https://www.jstor.org/stable/41494715 |archive-date=16 September 2021 |access-date=16 September 2021 |number=1, German Film Studies}}</ref> In 1991, Baker's life story, ''[[The Josephine Baker Story]]'', was broadcast on [[HBO]]. [[Lynn Whitfield]] portrayed Baker,<ref>{{cite web |first = Ken |last = Tucker |date = 15 March 1991 |title = The Josephine Baker Story |url = https://ew.com/article/1991/03/15/josephine-baker-story/ |access-date = 2 December 2021 |website = EW.com |language = en |archive-date = 2 December 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211202132222/https://ew.com/article/1991/03/15/josephine-baker-story/ |url-status = live }}</ref> and won an [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Special]]—becoming the first Black actress to win the award in this category. In the 1997 animated musical film ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'', Baker appears with her cheetah during the musical number "Paris Holds the Key (to Your Heart)".<ref>{{cite web |title = Anastasia – Paris Hold the Key (to Your Heart) Original |url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qsy9k3Z-CiY |via = [[YouTube]] |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-date = 5 May 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130505085833/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qsy9k3Z-CiY&gl=US&hl=en |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Saeed |first=Saeed |date=2021-08-25 |title=Who is Josephine Baker, the first black woman to enter France's Pantheon? |url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/arts-culture/music/2021/08/25/who-is-josephine-baker-the-first-black-woman-to-enter-frances-pantheon/ |access-date=2024-03-28 |website=The National |language=en}}</ref> In 2002, Baker was portrayed by [[Karine Plantadit]] in the biopic ''[[Frida (2002 film)|Frida.]]''<ref>{{cite web |title = 'Frida' |url = http://www.themoviespoiler.com/Spoilers/frida.html |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121005113857/http://themoviespoiler.com/Spoilers/frida.html |archive-date = 5 October 2012 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last = Ebert |first = Roger |title = 'Frida' |url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20021101/REVIEWS/211010302 |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130203083833/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20021101/REVIEWS/211010302 |url-status = dead |archive-date = February 3, 2013 |work = roger ebert |date = 1 November 2002 |access-date = 22 August 2012 }}</ref> A character who is based on Baker (topless, wearing the famous "banana skirt") appears in the opening sequence of the 2003 animated film ''[[The Triplets of Belleville]]'' ({{lang|fr|Les Triplettes de Belleville}}).<ref>{{cite web |title = The Triplets of Belleville (Les Triplettes de Belleville) |url = http://www.bonjourparis.com/story/triplets-belleville-les-triplettes-de-belleville |work = bonjourparis.com |access-date = 22 August 2012 |date = August 2009 |archive-date = 26 June 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120626152222/http://bonjourparis.com/story/triplets-belleville-les-triplettes-de-belleville/ |url-status = live }}</ref>

Her influence upon and assistance to the careers of the husband and wife dancers [[Carmen De Lavallade]] and [[Geoffrey Holder]] are discussed and illustrated in rare footage in the 2005 Linda Atkinson/Nick Doob [[documentary]], ''Carmen and Geoffrey''.<ref>{{cite web |last = Scheib |first = Ronnie |url = https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117939869.html?categoryid=1263&cs=1 |title = Review: 'Carmen and Geoffrey' |work = Variety |date = 13 March 2009 |access-date = 5 December 2013 |archive-date = 4 August 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090804115823/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117939869.html?categoryid=1263&cs=1 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://langston.bside.com/2009/films/carmenandgeoffrey_langston2009 |title = Langston Hughes African American Film Festival 2009: Carmen and Geoffrey |work = bside.com |access-date = 5 June 2016 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121021203113/http://langston.bside.com/2009/films/carmenandgeoffrey_langston2009 |archive-date = 21 October 2012 }}</ref> In 2011, [[Sonia Rolland]] portrayed Baker in the film ''[[Midnight in Paris]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title = The characters referenced in Woody Allen's "Midnight in Paris" (Part 16, Josephine Baker) |url = http://thedailyhatch.org/2011/06/24/the-characters-referenced-in-woody-allen%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%9Cmidnight-in-paris%E2%80%9D-part-16-josephine-baker |work = thedailyhatch.org |access-date = 22 August 2012 |date = 24 June 2011 |archive-date = 30 July 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120730094300/http://thedailyhatch.org/2011/06/24/the-characters-referenced-in-woody-allen%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%9Cmidnight-in-paris%E2%80%9D-part-16-josephine-baker/ |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last = Hammond |first = Margo |title = A 'Midnight in Paris' tour takes you back to the Paris of the '20s |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/travel/a-midnight-in-paris-tour-takes-you-back-to-the-paris-of-the-20s/2011/07/18/gIQAcDEHhI_story.html |newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] |date = 29 July 2011 |access-date = August 22, 2012 |archive-date = January 10, 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120110114532/http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/travel/a-midnight-in-paris-tour-takes-you-back-to-the-paris-of-the-20s/2011/07/18/gIQAcDEHhI_story.html |url-status = live }}</ref> In February 2017, Tiffany Daniels portrayed Baker in the "[[Timeless (TV series)|Timeless]]" television episode "The Lost Generation".<ref>{{cite web |first = Allison |last = Shoemaker |title = Timeless gets tipsy in a solid and unexpectedly timely episode |url = https://www.avclub.com/timeless-gets-tipsy-in-a-solid-and-unexpectedly-timely-1798190477 |work = The A.V. Club |date = 7 February 2017 |access-date = September 13, 2021 |archive-date = 13 September 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210913161923/https://www.avclub.com/timeless-gets-tipsy-in-a-solid-and-unexpectedly-timely-1798190477 |url-status = live }}</ref> In May 2020, Astrid Jones portrayed Baker in the {{lang|es|[[El ministerio del tiempo]]}} television episode "La memoria del tiempo" (The memory of time).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Astrid Jones actress |url=https://www.astridjones.com/en/astrid-jones-actress/ |access-date=2023-01-22 |website=Astrid Jones and her Creative Universe |language=en-US |archive-date=January 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230122144533/https://www.astridjones.com/en/astrid-jones-actress/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Baker is portrayed by actress [[Carra Patterson]] in "I Am.", the seventh episode of [[HBO]]'s television series ''[[Lovecraft Country (TV series)|Lovecraft Country]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |date = 27 September 2020 |title = 'Lovecraft Country' Recap: Shoot the Moon |url = https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-recaps/lovecraft-country-recap-episode-7-i-am-1066810/ |access-date = 28 September 2020 |magazine = Rolling Stone |archive-date = 28 September 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200928064536/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-recaps/lovecraft-country-recap-episode-7-i-am-1066810/ |url-status = live }}</ref>

A biopic about the life of Josephine Baker was announced in November 2022. It will be directed by French director [[Maïmouna Doucouré]] and produced by French production company [[Studiocanal]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goodfellow |first1=Melanie |title='Cuties' Director Maïmouna Doucouré To Write & Direct Josephine Baker Biopic For Studiocanal |url=https://deadline.com/2022/11/studiocanal-cuties-director-maimouna-doucoure-josephine-baker-bio-pic-1235162303/ |website=Deadline |access-date=8 May 2023 |date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=May 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230508195731/https://deadline.com/2022/11/studiocanal-cuties-director-maimouna-doucoure-josephine-baker-bio-pic-1235162303/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |last2=Hopewell |first2=John |title=Studiocanal Sets 'Cuties' Helmer Maïmouna Doucouré to Direct Josephine Baker Biopic Feature |url=https://variety.com/2022/global/global/studiocanal-maimouna-doucoure-josephine-baker-biopic-afm-1235421510/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=8 May 2023 |date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=May 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230508184741/https://variety.com/2022/global/global/studiocanal-maimouna-doucoure-josephine-baker-biopic-afm-1235421510/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Stage ===
In 1986, Helen Gelzer<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.danforthmusic.net/about |title = Biography – Helen Gelzer |work = danforthmusic.net |access-date = 5 June 2016 |archive-date = 21 March 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160321101845/http://www.danforthmusic.net/about/ |url-status = live }}</ref> portrayed Baker on the concept album ''Josephine'' – "a musical version of the life and times of Josephine Baker" with book, lyrics and music by Michael Wild.<ref>{{cite AV media |title = Helen Gelzer as 'Josephine': the concept musical |year = 1986 |medium=LP |oclc = 058782854 }}</ref> The musical director was Paul Maguire. The album was produced in conjunction with Baker's longtime friend Jack Hockett and Premier Box Office.<ref>{{cite web |title = Jack Hockett – Josephine Baker correspondence, etc. (dated 1967–1976) |work = Henry Hurford Janes – Josephine Baker Collection |publisher = Yale University Archives |at = Box: 2, Folder: 78 |url = https://archives.yale.edu/repositories/11/archival_objects/334114 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210824025554/https://archives.yale.edu/repositories/11/archival_objects/334114 |archive-date = 24 August 2021 }}</ref> A [[West End theatre|West End]] stage production of ''Josephine'' was premiered at the [[Fortune Theatre]] on June 4, 1989.<ref>''Composer, Known Only to God and Anna Neagle: the autobiography of Michael Wild as related to Cyd Slater,'' Michael Wild and Cyd Slater, {{ISBN|978-1-7242-5399-6}}, publ. 2018, Chapter 11, ''Josephine,'' pp. 121–127</ref> It was produced by Ian Liston and financed in conjunction with Jack Hockett and Premier Box Office. Jack Hockett died in 1988 before the show was staged. Heather Gillespie played the lead role of Josephine Baker, and Baker's husband Pepito was played by Roland Alexander. [[Peggy Phango]] played [[Bricktop]].<ref>''Josephine'' (state musical), Fortune Theatre, London, June 4, 1989 premier, Theatricalia: [https://theatricalia.com/play/jck/josephine/production/1an6 ''Josephine''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230525112959/https://theatricalia.com/play/jck/josephine/production/1an6 |date=May 25, 2023 }}, retrieved May 25, 2023</ref>

In 2006, [[Jérôme Savary]] produced a musical, ''A La Recherche de Josephine – New Orleans for Ever'' (Looking for Josephine), starring [[Nicolle Rochelle]].  The story revolved around the history of jazz and Baker's career.<ref>{{cite web |title = À la recherche de Joséphine |url = http://www.paris-tourist.com/en/rezension.php?id=55 |work = paris-tourist.com |date = 25 November 2006 |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-date = 10 December 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121210165732/http://www.paris-tourist.com/en/rezension.php?id=55 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Joséphine Baker |url = http://operachic.typepad.com/opera_chic/josphine_baker |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-date = 20 August 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120820143350/http://operachic.typepad.com/opera_chic/josphine_baker/ |url-status = live }}</ref> Also in 2006, [[Deborah Cox]] starred in the musical ''Josephine'' at Florida's [[Asolo Theatre]], directed and choreographed by Joey McKneely, with a book by [[Ellen Weston]] and Mark Hampton, music by [[Steve Dorff]] and lyrics by [[John Bettis]].<ref>{{cite web |last = Clement |first = Olivia |date = 11 May 2016 |title = The Verdict: What Do Critics Think of Josephine? |url = http://www.playbill.com/article/the-verdict-what-do-critics-think-of-josephine |access-date = 4 October 2020 |website = Playbill |language = en |archive-date = 10 October 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20201010145707/https://www.playbill.com/article/the-verdict-what-do-critics-think-of-josephine |url-status = live }}</ref> In July 2012, Cheryl Howard opened in ''The Sensational Josephine Baker'', written and performed by Howard and directed by Ian Streicher at the Beckett Theatre of Theatre Row on 42nd Street in New York City, just a few doors away from Chez Josephine.<ref>{{cite web |work = The Sensational Josephine Baker |url = http://www.thesensationaljosephinebaker.com |title = Latest News |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-date = 22 July 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120722042251/http://thesensationaljosephinebaker.com/ |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = The Sensational Josephine Baker |url = http://theater.nytimes.com/show/42001/The-Sensational-Josephine-Baker/overview |work = [[The New York Times]] |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120822075053/http://theater.nytimes.com/show/42001/The-Sensational-Josephine-Baker/overview |url-status = live }}</ref> In July 2013, [[Cush Jumbo]]'s debut play ''Josephine and I'' premiered at the [[Bush Theatre]], London.<ref>{{cite web |title = Bush Theatre |url = http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/production/josephine_i_ |access-date = 9 May 2013 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130616222313/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/production/josephine_i_ |archive-date = 16 June 2013 }}</ref> It was re-produced in New York City at The Public Theater's Joe's Pub from February 27 to April 5, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://publictheater.org/en/Tickets/Calendar/PlayDetailsCollection/1415/Josephine-and-I/?SiteTheme=Shakespeare |title = Josephine and I |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305210704/http://publictheater.org/en/Tickets/Calendar/PlayDetailsCollection/1415/Josephine-and-I/?SiteTheme=Shakespeare |archive-date = 5 March 2016 |work = publictheater.org |access-date = 13 October 2016 }}</ref>

In June 2016, ''Josephine, a burlesque cabaret dream play'' starring Tymisha Harris as Josephine Baker premiered at the 2016 [[San Diego International Fringe Festival|San Diego Fringe Festival]]. The show has since played across North America and had a limited off-Broadway run in January–February 2018 at [[SoHo Playhouse]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://josephinetheplay.com/ |title = Home |work = Josephine the play |access-date = 1 October 2018 |language = en |archive-date = 2 October 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181002021531/http://josephinetheplay.com/ |url-status = live }}</ref> In late February 2017, a new play about Baker's later years, ''The Last Night of Josephine Baker'' by playwright Vincent Victoria, opened in Houston, Texas,<ref>{{cite web |title = The Last Night of Josephine Baker |url = http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/event/the-last-night-of-josephine-baker/ |access-date = 3 June 2020 |website = OutSmart Magazine |date = 15 February 2017 |archive-date = 3 June 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200603062825/http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/event/the-last-night-of-josephine-baker/ |url-status = live }}</ref> starring Erica Young as "Past Josephine" and Jasmin Roland as "Present Josephine".<ref>{{cite web |last = Laird |first = Gary |date = 27 February 2017 |title = BWW Review: Josephine Reigns Supreme in 'The Last Night of Josephine Baker' at Midtown Arts Center |url = https://www.broadwayworld.com/houston/article/BWW-Review-Josephine-Reigns-Supreme-in-THE-LAST-NIGHT-OF-JOSEPHINE-BAKER-at-Midtown-Arts-Center-20170227 |access-date = 3 June 2020 |website = Broadway World Houston |archive-date = 3 June 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200603062334/https://www.broadwayworld.com/houston/article/BWW-Review-Josephine-Reigns-Supreme-in-THE-LAST-NIGHT-OF-JOSEPHINE-BAKER-at-Midtown-Arts-Center-20170227 |url-status = live }}</ref> Actress [[DeQuina Moore]] portrayed Baker in a biographic musical titled ''Josephine Tonight'' at [[The Ensemble Theatre]] in Houston, Texas, from June 27 to July 28, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |date = 12 June 2019 |title = The Ensemble Theatre Elevates the Life of Josephine Baker in Season Finale Musical 'Josephine Tonight' |url = http://stylemagazine.com/news/2019/jun/12/ensemble-theatre-elevates-life-josephine-baker-sea/ |access-date = 3 June 2020 |website = Houston Style Magazine |archive-date = 3 June 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200603061323/http://stylemagazine.com/news/2019/jun/12/ensemble-theatre-elevates-life-josephine-baker-sea/ |url-status = live }}</ref> In September 2021, [[Theatre Royal, Bath]], in conjunction with [[Oxford Playhouse]] and [[Wales Millennium Centre]] produced a UK touring production of ''Josephine'' co-written by Leona Allen and Jesse Briton who also directed the show. It toured the UK and featured Ebony Feare in the lead role as Josephine Baker.<ref>{{cite web |title = Josephine – Theatre Royal Bath |url = https://www.theatreroyal.org.uk/josephine/ |access-date = 23 October 2021 |website = www.theatreroyal.org.uk |archive-date = 23 October 2021 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211023222730/https://www.theatreroyal.org.uk/josephine/ |url-status = live }}</ref>

Since 2016  Dynamite Lunchbox Entertainment of Orlando Florida has been touring ''Josephine, a burlesque cabaret dream play'',<ref>{{Cite web |last=admin |title=Home |url=https://josephinetheplay.com/ |access-date=2023-06-01 |website=Josephine the play |language=en |archive-date=June 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230601135419/https://josephinetheplay.com/ |url-status=live }}</ref> co-created by and starring Tymisha Harris, to Fringe Festivals around Canada and the U.S. It played at the Montreal Fringe Festival in 2022. It is part of the 2022–2023 official season at the Segal Centre for the Performing Arts in Montreal (Spring 2023) as ''Josephine, A Musical Cabaret''.

=== Literature ===
Baker appears in her role as a member of the French Resistance in [[Johannes Mario Simmel]]'s 1960 novel, {{lang|de|Es muss nicht immer Kaviar sein}} ({{lang|fr|C'est pas toujours du caviar}}).<ref>{{cite journal |title = Es muss nicht immer Kaviar sein |journal = [[The New York Times Book Review]] |year = 1965 |volume = 70 |page = 150 }}</ref> The 2004 [[erotic literature|erotic novel]] ''Scandalous'' by British author Angela Campion uses Baker as its [[heroine]] and is inspired by Baker's sexual exploits and later adventures in the French Resistance. In the novel, Baker, working with a fictional [[Black Canadian]] lover named Drummer Thompson, foils a plot by French fascists in 1936 Paris.<ref>{{cite book |last = Campion |first = Angela |title = Scandalous |year = 2004 |publisher = Brown Skin Books |isbn = 978-0-9544866-2-4 }}</ref> Baker was heavily featured in the 2012 book ''Josephine's Incredible Shoe & The Blackpearls'' by Peggi Eve Anderson-Randolph.<ref>{{cite book |title = Josephine's Incredible Shoe and the Blackpearls |volume = 1 |isbn = 978-1-4775-7015-9 |last1 = Anderson-Randolph |first1 = Peggi Eve |year = 2012 |publisher = CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform }}</ref> In his novel ''Noire, la neige'', Marseille,  Editions Parenthèses, {{ISBN|978-2-86364-648-9}}, Pascal Rannou evokes the relationship between [[Valaida Snow]] and Josephine Baker, who is one of the main characters of this story.

=== Music ===
The Italian-Belgian francophone singer composer [[Salvatore Adamo]] pays tribute to Baker with the song "Noël Sur Les Milandes" (album ''Petit Bonheur'' – EMI 1970). The British band Sailor paid tribute on their 1974 self-titled debut album ''Sailor'' with the Georg Kajanus song "Josephine Baker" who "...stunned the world at the Folies Bergère..." The title track of the 1987 Premiata Forneria Marconi album ''Miss Baker'' was written in honor of the American dancer Josephine Baker. British singer-songwriter [[Al Stewart]] wrote "Josephine Baker" about her, a song which appears on the album ''[[Last Days of the Century]]'', from 1988.

[[Beyoncé Knowles]] has portrayed Baker on various occasions. During the 2006 [[Fashion Rocks]] show, Knowles performed "Dejá Vu" in a revised version of the ''Danse banane'' costume. In Knowles's video for "[[Naughty Girl (Beyoncé Knowles song)|Naughty Girl]]", she is seen dancing in a huge champagne glass à la Baker. In ''I Am ... Yours: An Intimate Performance at Wynn Las Vegas,'' Beyoncé lists Baker as an influence of a section of her live show.<ref>{{cite web |title = This Date in Music History: April 12 {{!}} Legend Josephine Baker passes away and Vince Gill is born |url = http://www.citybeat.com/cincinnati/blog-3283-this_date_in_music_h.html |work = citybeat.com |first=Mike|last=Breen|date=12 April 2012|access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121013154136/http://www.citybeat.com/cincinnati/blog-3283-this_date_in_music_h.html |archive-date = 13 October 2012 |url-status = dead }}</ref> In 2010, [[Keri Hilson]] portrayed Baker in her single "[[Pretty Girl Rock]]".<ref>{{cite web |title = Keri Hilson Pays Tribute To Janet, TLC, Supremes In 'Pretty Girl Rock' Video |url = http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/hip-hop-media-training/keri-hilson-pays-tribute-to-janet-tlc-supremes-in-pretty-girl-rock-video.html |work = yahoo music |date = 17 November 2010 |access-date = 22 August 2012 |archive-date = 3 October 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121003063042/http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/hip-hop-media-training/keri-hilson-pays-tribute-to-janet-tlc-supremes-in-pretty-girl-rock-video.html |url-status = live }}</ref> In January 2022, Laquita Mitchell sang the title role in the [[Opera in New Orleans#The modern era|New Orleans Opera]] production of ''Josephine'' by [[Tom Cipullo]].<ref name="2022-01-03-opWire">{{cite web |title = Artist of the Week: Laquita Mitchell |url = https://operawire.com/artist-of-the-week-laquita-mitchell/ |access-date = 10 March 2022 |first = Francisco |last = Salazar |website = operawire.com |date = 3 January 2022 |archive-date = 8 March 2022 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20220308032607/https://operawire.com/artist-of-the-week-laquita-mitchell/ |url-status = live }}</ref>

=== Artworks ===
In 1927, [[Alexander Calder]] created ''Josephine Baker (III),'' a wire sculpture of Baker, which is now displayed at the [[Museum of Modern Art]].<ref>{{cite web |title = Alexander Calder. Josephine Baker (III). Paris, c. 1927 |url = https://www.moma.org/collection/works/81896 |access-date = 20 January 2021 |publisher = The Museum of Modern Art |language = en |archive-date = 14 December 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20201214130030/https://www.moma.org/collection/works/81896 |url-status = live }}</ref> A nude portrait of Baker by [[Jean de Botton]] was the "cynosure for all eyes" when it was shown at the [[Salon d'Automne]] in Paris in 1931.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bd6t517730q/f5 "Fall Salon at Grand Palais Crowded as Parisians View 2,750 Canvases"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230525203703/https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bd6t517730q/f5 |date=May 25, 2023 }}, ''International Herald Tribune,'' Nov. 1, 1931, p. 5.</ref> When auctioned in Paris in 2021 the painting set a world record (EUR 179,200) for the artist.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.ader-paris.fr/actualite/81989| title = 179,200 € Pour le Portrait Inédit de Joséphine Baker aux Enchères| website = ader-paris.fr| date = November 19, 2021| access-date = May 25, 2023| archive-date = May 25, 2023| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20230525203703/https://www.ader-paris.fr//actualite/81989| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.photo.rmn.fr/CS.aspx?VP3=SearchResult&VBID=2CMFCIX3A7AAKK&SMLS=1&RW=1378&RH=937 Two drawings by de Botton depicting Josephine Baker] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230526072229/https://www.photo.rmn.fr/CS.aspx?VP3=SearchResult&VBID=2CMFCIX3A7AAKK&SMLS=1&RW=1378&RH=937 |date=May 26, 2023 }}, also from 1931, are conserved at the Musée franco-américain du château de [[Blérancourt]].</ref> [[Henri Matisse]] created a mural-sized cut paper artwork titled ''[[La Négresse]]'' (1952–1953), possibly inspired by Baker.<ref>{{cite book |last1 = Hauptman |first1 = Jodi |title = Henri Matisse: the cut-outs |publisher = The Museum of Modern Art |editor1-last = Buchberg |editor1-first = Karl D. |editor2-last = Cullinan |editor2-first = Nicholas |editor3-last = Hauptman |editor3-first = Jodi |editor4-last = Sirota |editor4-first = Nicholas |editor5-last = Friedman |editor5-first = Samantha |editor6-last = Frigeri |editor6-first = Flavia |year = 2014 |isbn = 978-0-87070-915-9 |location = New York |pages = 196 |chapter = Bodies and Waves |oclc = 859305247 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last = Millard |first = Charles W. |date = 1978 |title = The Matisse Cut-Out |journal = The Hudson Review |volume = 31 |issue = 2 |pages = 326 |doi = 10.2307/3849913 |jstor = 3849913 |issn = 0018-702X }}</ref> [[Hassan Musa]] depicted Baker in a 1994 series of paintings called ''Who needs Bananas?''<ref>{{cite web |first = Julie |last = Crenn |date = 21 November 2010 |language = fr |url = http://www.africultures.com/php/index.php?nav=article&no=9819# |title = Icône de la constellation Noire: Joséphine Baker |work = Africultures.com |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101206185845/http://www.africultures.com/php/index.php?nav=article&no=9819 |archive-date = 6 December 2010 }}</ref> Season 14 of the Duolingo French Podcast is titled The Secret Life of Josephine Baker. The season finale was released in November 2023.

